Imagine a very long web page with a lot of sections (i.e., an HTML specification on a single page). When the user requests a specific section (e.g., page.html#section7), how would it be if the web server first streams this section and then the others?
Streaming order:
1. Beginning of the HTML document up to <body>
2. HTML for section 7
3. HTML for sections 1, 2, 3, etc.
Then the browser would make sure that sections 1 to 6 are displayed *above* section 7 on the web page.
Does that make sense? Would that be helpful?
The linked section (#section7) should be rendered as quickly as possible without having to implement elements again with JavaScript. I simply want to have an extra long HTML document, but the linked sections should be rendered as quickly as possible. With HTML, that should work.
The content could be streamed in this way, and then the browser would insert all <contents> into the <div>.
<div id=sec1></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
etc.
<div id=sec7>section 7…</div>
<contents for=sec1>section 1…</contents>
<contents for=sec2>section 2…</contents>
etc.
It would not be streamed sequentially, but the browser would assemble the HTML document as if it had been streamed sequentially.
@user22 You can also reorder documents without JS. You should not use the hash part of the URL if you want the server to do something, but you can use query string search parameters so the server knows which section you want first. When reordering the parts, you have several options:
1. Use CSS
2. Use a template with sections
@user23 Yes. The problem is that the visual order (what the user sees) does not match the DOM order. It would be useful to have an HTML function that allows streaming out of order, but the browser then arranges the content in the DOM order.
But the idea with slots looks promising. I'll try that.
@user22 oh, do you want the browser to sort out the DOM order?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first, just so the user can see it as soon as possible. If that could happen without affecting the DOM order, that would be good, then the browser would make sure that the resulting DOM order matches the visual order.
So section 7 should be streamed first, but the end result should look as if all sections were streamed in order.
@user22 @user23 Take a look at PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
